Let ∑ ={a, b}

then ∑* = { ε, a, b, aa, ba, bb, ...................}

"Set of all strings over any finite alphabet are <strong>Countable</strong>". Therefore, ∑* is countable.
Since there exist an enumeration procedure using which all the string of the language can be generated, which means each string can be counted in finite number of steps.

So, ∑* is countably infinite But 2<sup>Σ*</sup> is Uncountable, which can be proved using Diagonalization Method. This theorem says-  "If ∑* is countably infinite then 2<sup>Σ*</sup> is Uncountable".

